<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-757-834  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 757 834.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Industrial Engineering  August 1990 v22 n8 p26(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Moscow diary: star is rising for industrial engineering andindustrial engineers. (potential for industrial engineers inRussia, part 1 of 2)(includes related article on excerpts fromPresident Mikhail Gorbachev's report to the 27th Congress ofCommunist Party of the Soviet Union)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Badiru, Adedeji B.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A US delegation of industrial and economic developmentprofessionals toured several Soviet industrial plants in Moscow,Kiev and Minsk.andP;  The delegation found that there are many ways inwhich formal industrial engineering practices can benefit theUSSR.andP;  Perestroika and glasnost have created businessopportunities for industrial engineers and each Soviet republic isnow free to establish business contacts without going throughMoscow.andP;  Gorbachev's report to the 27th Congress of CommunistParty of the Soviet Union signifies the potential for theapplication of industrial engineering practices which mayadditionally contribute to industrial reform.andP;  The Institute ofIndustrial Engineers should prepare itself to take a lead inexpanding industrial engineering techniques in the USSR, where noformal training programs currently exist.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Soviet UnionEngineeringIndustry AnalysisBusiness PlanningMarket AnalysisInternational TradeForecasting.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>